column1: Which condom brand is best to use?

After 45 hours of research, including reading hundreds of reviews of 62 top-rated, best-selling condoms and interviewing nine experts, including a chemical engineer and two sex workers—and having 44 volunteers test 40 total types since 2015—we found the LifeStyles Skyn to be the best average-size condom. column1: How to put on a condom?
column2: Roll the condom on when your penis is erect (hard), but BEFORE it touches your partner’s mouth or genital area (vulva, vagina, anus, buttocks, and upper thighs) — and wear it the whole time you’re having sex. This helps protect you from STDs that are transmitted through skin-to-skin touching. It also prevents contact with pre-ejaculate (pre-cum), which can have STD germs and may rarely contain sperm that can cause pregnancy.

column1: can you get pregnant while on you period
column2: Here’s the deal: You're most likely to get pregnant when you have sex right before and during ovulation (when an egg is released). Ovulation happens in the middle of your menstrual cycle, usually about 14 days before your period starts. The average menstrual cycle is about 25-30 days, but it can be shorter or longer. It’s important to keep in mind that ovulation is different from person to person. If your periods are irregular, this can make it harder to keep track of when ovulation happens. And if you have a shorter menstrual cycle, you can have a higher chance of getting pregnant from sex during your period.

column1: What do I need to know about safe and healthy relationships

column1: How do I understand and manage my feelings and attractions
column2: Feelings are signals from the body that help us understand ourselves and make good decisions. Here are 5 ways to practice being more aware of your emotions: 1) Notice and name your feelings. To start, just notice how you feel as things happen. Say the name of the feeling to yourself. You might feel proud when something goes well. Or disappointed if you don't do well on a test. 2) Track one emotion. Pick one emotion — like feeling glad. Track it all day. Notice how often you feel it. Maybe you're glad when something good happens. Or glad when a friend shows up. Every time you feel glad, make a mental note to yourself or write it down. 3) Keep a feelings journal. Take a few minutes each day to write about how you feel and why. Writing about your feelings helps you get to know them better. Make art, write poetry, or compose music to express an emotion you feel. 4) Talk to a therapist. If you're finding it difficult to understand or manage your emotions, consider talking to a therapist. They can help you explore your feelings, provide support, and guide you in developing healthier ways of coping with emotions.

column1: Can your penis be libido at young age
column2: Testosterone is an important hormone in men and is responsible for regulating sexual development. Testosterone deficiency, or low testosterone, can contribute to a decreased sex drive and erectile dysfunction, as well as fatigue, depression, and diminishing muscle mass. While low testosterone is more common among older men, young men should not dismiss it. Recent evidence shows roughly 20% of adolescent and young adult males have low testosterone.

column1: Why is my left nut hurting me
column2: Testicle pain can result from various causes, including nerve damage, sexually transmitted infections (STIs), gangrene, swelling, hernias, kidney stones, inflammation, enlarged veins (varicocele), or fluid accumulation in the testicle (hydrocele). A particularly serious cause of testicle pain is a condition called testicular torsion. Testicular torsion occurs when the spermatic cord, which supplies blood to the testicle, becomes twisted. This twist cuts off the blood supply to the testicle, causing sudden and severe pain, along with swelling. Testicular torsion is a medical emergency, as prolonged loss of blood flow can lead to permanent damage or loss of the testicle. Immediate surgical intervention is often required to untwist the cord and restore blood flow.

column1: What’s the difference between love and lust?

column1: How do I know if I’m addicted to porn and what should I do about it?
column2: Porn addiction is surprisingly common; many doctors classify it as a hypersexual disorder and similar mental health disorders like sex addiction or excessive masturbation. Watching porn doesn’t automatically lead to porn addiction. However, if a person begins to prioritize porn over their well-being, it may be a sign that they need help. While inpatient care is commonly associated with substance abuse treatment, porn addiction requires a less intense approach. Therapy and counseling from mental health professionals have proven to be the most effective treatment options for porn addiction.

column1: How effective are birth control pills at preventing pregnancy?
column2: If you use it perfectly, the pill is 99% effective. But people aren't perfect and it's easy to forget or miss pills — so in reality the pill is about 93% effective. That means about 7 out of 100 pill users get pregnant each year.

column1: Can you get pregnant from pre-ejaculation/pre-cum?
column2: You can definitely get pregnant even if the guy pulls out before he comes. Guys can leak a bit of sperm out of the penis before ejaculation. This is called pre-ejaculate ("pre-cum"). So even if a guy pulls out before he ejaculates, a girl can still become pregnant.

column1: How does the morning-after pill work?
column2: The morning after pill stops or delays ovulation to prevent pregnancy. Ovulation is when your ovary releases an egg. The morning after pill is for emergency contraception only. It is not an abortion pill.

column1: Can you get STIs from oral sex?
column2: Yes. Many STIs and other infections are spread through oral sex. Anyone exposed to an infected partner can get an STI in the mouth, throat, genitals, or rectum.

column1: What are the symptoms of common STIs?
column2: an unusual discharge from your vagina, penis or anus, pain when peeing, lumps or skin growths around your genitals or bottom (anus), a rash, unusual vaginal bleeding, itchy genitals or anus, blisters, sores or warts around your genitals or anus.

column1: How often should I get tested for STIs?
column2: National guidelines recommend yearly screening for: Sexually active women under age 25. Women older than 25 are at increased risk of STIs, such as having sex with a new partner or multiple partners. Men who have sex with men.

column1: What should I do if I think I might be pregnant?
column2: If you think you might be pregnant, you should take a pregnancy test so that you can find out for sure. You can buy one from a supermarket or pharmacy, or get one for free from your GP practice or local sexual health clinic.

column1: How do I use a pregnancy test, and when is the best time to take it?
column2: If you don't know when your next period is due, do the test at least 21 days after you last had unprotected sex. Some very sensitive pregnancy tests can be used even before you miss a period. You can do a pregnancy test on a sample of urine collected at any time of the day. It doesn't have to be in the morning.
column3:
Test in the morning using your first urine of the day, as hCG levels are more concentrated at that time.
Wait until at least the first day of a missed period for more accurate results.
Use your first morning pee.
Avoid drinking a lot of fluids before taking the test.
Make sure the test isn't past its expiration date.

column1: What are the side effects of hormonal birth control?
column2: 1) hormonal changes: Birth control pills and patches work by altering your hormones. This may lead to unwanted sides effects such as acne and fatigue. or elimination of unwanted symptoms. 2) mood changes: Birth control can affect your mood. While some women experience reduced anxiety, others can experience depression. 3) migraines: Birth control may make migraines worse or better, depending on the kind you take. This can be temporary or long-lasting. 4) reduced acne: Estrogen and progestin can make acne clear up for some women, while others find it makes their acne worse. 5) breast changes: Breast changes are a possibility when taking birth control. The most commonly reported symptoms include breast tenderness and enlargement. 6) appetite changes: There may be an increase or decrease in your appetite. depending on which kind of birth control you use. 7) blood pressure: It's important to have your blood pressure checked regularly, as there's a risk of high blood pressure from taking birth control.

What should I do if I forget to take a birth control pill?
column2: If you forget to take a birth control pill, you should: Take the missed pill as soon as you remember. Take the next pill at your usual time, even if it means taking two on the same day. If you miss any of the first 21 pills in your pack, you may need to use an alternate birth control method, such as a condom, for the next seven days. If you find that you frequently forget to take your pill, it may be better off using another form of birth control.

column1: How can I prevent STIs while using sex toys?
column2: To prevent STIs with sex toys, you can: Keep sex toys clean by washing them after each use. Cover penetrative sex toys, such as vibrators, with a fresh condom each time they are used. Using condoms with your sex toys is less complicated than you might imagine. If you’re using something like an anal plug or a vibrator, simply grab a condom and roll it on the way you would a for a penis. It won’t affect the power of vibrating toys.

column1: What’s the best way to store and handle condoms?
column2: Store condoms a cool, dry place. Put the condom on before your penis or sex toy makes contact with your partner’s mouth or genitals. Check for tears before using your condom. Use a water or silicone-based lube (if you’re using latex condoms). Put on a  new condom if it breaks or falls off.

column1: What are the risks of having multiple sexual partners?
column2: According to a 2015 study published in the journal PLoS One, having unprotected sex with multiple sexual partners (MSP) is the greatest risk factor for human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and other sexually transmitted infections (STIs) among youths.

column1: Can sexual activity cause physical pain?

Causes in men may include: Infection of the prostate or bladder, Prostatitis, Interstitial Pystitis.

column1: What is a pap smear, and why is it important?
column2: A Pap smear is a test that helps doctors catch problems in the cells of a woman’s cervix before they turn into something serious, like cancer. By finding these changes early, doctors can treat them more easily and stop cancer from spreading. That’s why it’s so important for women to get regular Pap tests and pelvic exams—they’re a key part of staying healthy.

column1: How do I manage menstrual cycles while on hormonal birth control?
column2: To manage your period while on birth control, it's good to know how your specific method works since it can make your periods lighter, more regular, or even stop them. If you’re taking pills, stick to the schedule and take them at the same time each day. Some birth control types let you skip your period by starting a new pack right away, but it's best to check with your doctor before doing that. You might notice some spotting or irregular periods at first, but this usually settles down. It’s also helpful to track your cycle so you know what’s normal for you, and reach out to your doctor if something feels off.

column1: What are the long-term effects of using hormonal contraception?
column2: Long-term use of hormonal birth control can make periods lighter and less painful, though irregular bleeding might happen at first. Fertility usually returns to normal after stopping, and while it can lower the risk of some cancers, it might slightly increase the risk of others. There are also potential risks for heart health, especially in smokers, and some people might notice weight gain, mood changes, or differences in acne. These effects vary, so it's important to talk to a doctor if you have any concerns.

column1: How do I know if a birth control method is working?
column2: You know your birth control is working if you’re not getting pregnant and your periods are regular (if they haven’t stopped). As long as you’re using it correctly and not having any weird side effects, it’s likely doing its job. If something feels off, talk to your doctor.

column1: What are the symptoms of a UTI versus an STI? *
column2: UTI symptoms include frequent, painful urination, a burning sensation when you pee, and cloudy or smelly urine. You might also feel lower abdominal pain. For STIs, look out for unusual discharge, pain during sex or urination, itching, or sores around the genitals. If you notice any of these, it’s smart to see a doctor to get checked out.

column1: Can sex affect my skin or acne?
column2: Yes and no. The truth is during puberty, the level of sexual hormones is more abundant and they may heighten your sexual desire. Sexual hormones also increase the production of sebum. If bacteria (known as P. acnes) are present together with sebum (oil), then this can trigger acne development.

column1: How soon can I start using birth control after having sex?
column2: However, if you don’t begin your pill pack until after your period has started, you’ll need to wait seven days before having unprotected sex. If you have sex during this time, be sure to use a barrier method, like a condom, for the first week.

column1: What’s the difference between STI tests and regular health checkups?
column2: STI tests focus on detecting sexually transmitted infections like chlamydia, gonorrhea, and HIV, typically involving blood tests, urine samples, or swabs from genital areas. They’re often recommended for sexually active individuals, particularly those with multiple partners, or when symptoms suggest an infection. Regular health checkups provide a general assessment of overall health, including vital signs, blood tests for cholesterol and glucose levels, physical exams, and lifestyle discussions. These checkups aim to catch potential health issues early and promote preventive care.

column1: What is the pull out method, and is it reliable?
column2: The withdrawal method, also known as pulling out, is a form of natural birth control that involves withdrawing the penis from the vagina prior to ejaculation. However, it is not very reliable, working about 78% of the time1234. It is recommended to use other forms of contraception, such as condoms, to prevent pregnancy and protect against STDs

column1: How effective are different types of contraceptives at preventing STIs and pregnancy?
column2: Contraceptives work differently for preventing pregnancy and STIs. Condoms are effective for both pregnancy and reducing the risk of most STIs, though they don’t fully protect against STIs spread through skin-to-skin contact. Diaphragms and cervical caps are okay for pregnancy prevention but don’t do much for STIs. Birth control pills, patches, injections, and implants are great at preventing pregnancy but don’t offer any protection against STIs.

column1: Can sex affect my future fertility?
column2: Sex itself generally doesn’t affect future fertility. However, factors related to sex, like STIs, can impact fertility if they’re not treated. STIs can cause complications that might affect reproductive health, so it’s important to practice safe sex and get regular check-ups. If you have any concerns about fertility, talking to a doctor can provide more personalized advice.

column1: How can I talk to my doctor about sexual health?
column2: Be honest and straightforward with your doctor about your concerns. Start talking about sexual health at the beginning of your appointment to make it easier. Remember, your doctor is there to help and keeps everything private, so you don’t need to worry. If something isn’t clear, just ask them to explain it more.
column3: To talk to a doctor about sexual health, you should be assertive and advocate for your own health1. If your primary physician cannot address all of your questions or concerns, they should put you in contact with other medical professionals who can help1. Communication about sexual health is a complex matter influenced by many factors2. It is important for providers to understand their own feelings about sexual matters, be willing to speak truthfully at the risk of increasing their own vulnerability, and be able to listen and interpret patients’ sexual values, experiences, and concerns

column1: How can I handle an unexpected pregnancy?
column2: Handling an unexpected pregnancy can be tough. Start by talking to someone you trust for support. See a doctor to confirm the pregnancy and discuss your options. Think about whether you want to continue the pregnancy, consider adoption, or explore abortion. Reflect on how each option fits with your goals and situation. Seeking help from a counselor or support group can also be really useful.

column1: Can I use contraceptives if I have certain health conditions?
column2: It depends on the health condition. Some contraceptives might be okay, while others could have risks. For example, hormonal methods might not be recommended if you have certain health issues like high blood pressure or a history of blood clots. Always check with your doctor to find the safest and most effective option for your specific situation.

column1: What are the risks associated with unprotected sex?
column2: Unprotected sex can result in unintended pregnancy and raise your risk of STIs. It’s important to use protection, like condoms, to lower these risks and stay safe. Regular check-ups and getting tested can also help maintain your sexual health.

column1: Can you get STIs from sharing sex toys?
column2: Yes, sharing sex toys can spread STIs if they aren’t cleaned properly or covered with a new condom each time. To reduce the risk, use condoms on the toys and clean them thoroughly before and after each use. This helps prevent the spread of infections and keeps things safe.

column1: How do I choose the right birth control method for me?
column2: To choose the right birth control, consider your health, lifestyle, and how often you want to manage it. Think about how effective the method is at preventing pregnancy and whether it protects against STIs. Also, be aware of potential side effects. Talking to your doctor can help you find the best fit for you.

column1: What’s the difference between a regular STI test and a rapid STI test?
column2: A rapid STI test detects results within minutes, instead of days. Traditional STI or STD tests require your healthcare provider to send a sample to the lab for analysis. This process can take five to seven days, during which time you may feel anxiety or confusion about what to do or who to tell while you wait for results.

column1: How do I address and manage sexual health concerns with a healthcare provider?
column2: Understand their own feelings about sexual matters Be willing to speak truthfully at the risk of increasing their own vulnerability Be able to listen and interpret patients’ sexual values, experiences, and concerns Be willing to reply honestly and clearly to patients’ sexual concerns

column1: What are some safe practices for using sex toys?
column2: These methods can include: using external or internal condoms for penetrative intercourse, including with sex toys using condoms or dental dams for oral sex using gloves for manual stimulation or penetration

column1: How can I prevent and treat sexually transmitted infections?
column2: Avoid sharing towels or underclothing. Wash before and after intercourse. Get a vaccination for hepatitis B. This is a series of three shots. Get tested for HIV. If you have a problem with drug or alcohol abuse, get help.

column1: What’s the difference between STI and STD?
column2: STIs and STDs are terms often used interchangeably, but they have specific meanings. STIs are infections spread through sexual activity, including oral, vaginal, or anal sex, and any genital contact. They’re common, preventable, and treatable, with many being curable. STD, on the other hand, refers to a disease resulting from an STI.

column1: How can I find out if I’m at risk for any sexual health issues?
column2: Determining if you’re at risk for sexual health issues involves several steps, including self-assessment, medical evaluations, and awareness of your personal risk factors.

column1: Can I get pregnant if I have sex during my period?
column2: Yes — it’s possible to get pregnant if you have unprotected sex during your period. But it's not super common, especially during the very beginning of your period.

column1: How does my menstrual cycle affect my sexual desire?
column2: The menstrual cycle affects sexual desire due to hormonal fluctuations. Oestrogen and progesterone levels shift throughout the cycle, impacting mood, physical comfort, and libido

column2: To handle anxiety about having sex for the first time, you can make a plan to address your fears, like challenging negative thoughts or learning more about anatomy. Communicate openly with your partner about your feelings, and try to relax and have fun by being playful.
